951
00:39:49,550 --> 00:39:52,350
That's the key to whether or not

952
00:39:53,670 --> 00:39:54,350
symmetries...

953
00:39:58,630 --> 00:40:01,330
whether or not symmetries

954
00:40:01,330 --> 00:40:04,210
create degeneracies of energy levels.

955
00:40:04,510 --> 00:40:06,130
We've seen in this case

956
00:40:06,130 --> 00:40:09,250
that two symmetries,

957
00:40:09,410 --> 00:40:12,350
rotational symmetry together with reflection symmetry,

958
00:40:12,650 --> 00:40:15,970
tell us that there are degeneracies of the energy levels.

959
00:40:16,230 --> 00:40:18,410
That M and minus M

960
00:40:18,410 --> 00:40:19,650
have to have the same energy.

961
00:40:20,429 --> 00:40:21,250
That's a pattern.

962
00:40:22,130 --> 00:40:23,069
It's also a theorem,

963
00:40:23,250 --> 00:40:24,949
but we'll...

964
00:40:24,949 --> 00:40:27,170
I don't think we'll do the theorem right now.

965
00:40:28,090 --> 00:40:30,270
Does this mean that any Heisenberg pair

966
00:40:30,270 --> 00:40:33,290
generates degeneracies?

967
00:40:38,190 --> 00:40:39,890
A Heisenberg pair like x and p?

968
00:40:40,730 --> 00:40:41,130
Well,

969
00:40:41,130 --> 00:40:43,050
the problem is that x and p are not conserved.

970
00:40:45,230 --> 00:40:45,630
Right.

971
00:40:45,710 --> 00:40:47,170
And they're not symmetries in themselves.

972
00:40:48,430 --> 00:40:52,590
In the case of a particle

973
00:40:52,590 --> 00:40:55,410
not having a magnetic field,

974
00:40:56,910 --> 00:40:58,170
then angular momentum,

975
00:40:58,170 --> 00:40:58,730
rotation,

976
00:40:58,730 --> 00:40:59,810
and reflection

977
00:40:59,810 --> 00:41:00,850
are both symmetries.

978
00:41:01,090 --> 00:41:03,150
They both commute with a Hamiltonian.

979
00:41:03,230 --> 00:41:05,890
They both are conserved.

980
00:41:07,470 --> 00:41:12,570
x and p are typically and generally not conserved.

981
00:41:12,730 --> 00:41:13,490
If they were,

982
00:41:13,490 --> 00:41:14,750
then the answer would be yes.

983
00:41:17,110 --> 00:41:18,390
Then the answer would be yes.

984
00:41:18,390 --> 00:41:18,890
Yeah.

985
00:41:19,450 --> 00:41:19,930
Okay.

986
00:41:20,570 --> 00:41:23,850
We're going to study an example in some detail tonight.

987
00:41:24,550 --> 00:41:25,850
I think we'll get through it.

988
00:41:27,910 --> 00:41:28,390
Oh,

989
00:41:28,390 --> 00:41:28,790
let's...

990
00:41:28,790 --> 00:41:28,930
Well,

991
00:41:28,930 --> 00:41:30,730
let's just write down

992
00:41:33,790 --> 00:41:37,130
just some formal observations of what I mean.

993
00:41:37,790 --> 00:41:39,730
Supposing you have two symmetries.

994
00:41:39,870 --> 00:41:40,070
Now,

995
00:41:40,070 --> 00:41:41,210
what does it mean to have a symmetry?

996
00:41:41,650 --> 00:41:43,850
Let's call the two symmetries A and B.

997
00:41:44,930 --> 00:41:47,590
The A and B stand for operators.

998
00:41:48,910 --> 00:41:50,730
Operators that act on the state vectors.

999
00:41:50,930 --> 00:41:53,810
They could stand for infinitesimal generators,

1000
00:41:54,170 --> 00:41:56,290
or they could stand for

1001
00:41:56,290 --> 00:41:58,410
the full operation of the symmetry.

1002
00:41:58,890 --> 00:41:59,830
A and B.

1003
00:42:00,350 --> 00:42:02,650
Let's say they refer to the generators.

1004
00:42:03,010 --> 00:42:07,030
Let's take the case of where there are small versions

1005
00:42:07,030 --> 00:42:08,730
of the transformations.

1006
00:42:11,430 --> 00:42:12,030
Then,

1007
00:42:12,030 --> 00:42:13,790
to say they're symmetries means

1008
00:42:14,390 --> 00:42:16,750
that both of them commute with a Hamiltonian.

1009
00:42:26,830 --> 00:42:28,670
It does not in itself

1010
00:42:28,670 --> 00:42:30,510
say that A commutes with B.

1011
00:42:31,110 --> 00:42:32,110
In general,

1012
00:42:32,110 --> 00:42:34,270
here's an example where they didn't.

1013
00:42:35,450 --> 00:42:40,790
Commutator of A with B may be non-zero,

1014
00:42:41,530 --> 00:42:43,070
and there are two possibilities.

1015
00:42:44,530 --> 00:42:46,730
Both possibilities will lead to degeneracy,

1016
00:42:46,750 --> 00:42:48,670
but let's think of two possibilities.

1017
00:42:49,010 --> 00:42:50,270
In one possibility,

1018
00:42:50,270 --> 00:42:52,310
the commutator of A and B

1019
00:42:52,310 --> 00:42:54,290
may be A itself,

1020
00:42:54,290 --> 00:42:55,870
it may be B itself,

1021
00:42:56,210 --> 00:42:57,830
or it may be some

1022
00:42:57,830 --> 00:42:59,450
linear combination of A and B.

1023
00:43:00,170 --> 00:43:02,650
That does not lead to a new symmetry.

1024
00:43:02,970 --> 00:43:05,210
It doesn't lead to a new operator.

1025
00:43:05,370 --> 00:43:06,720
It just leads to a

1026
00:43:06,720 --> 00:43:08,070
linear combination of the old ones.

1027
00:43:09,110 --> 00:43:10,730
But let's suppose that it

1028
00:43:10,730 --> 00:43:12,350
leads to a genuinely new operator

1029
00:43:12,350 --> 00:43:16,730
that cannot be written as a linear commutator.

1030
00:43:16,750 --> 00:43:17,670
It's a linear combination of A and B.

1031
00:43:17,730 --> 00:43:18,430
Let's call it C.

1032
00:43:23,190 --> 00:43:23,590
Okay,

1033
00:43:23,590 --> 00:43:24,870
first theorem.

1034
00:43:25,530 --> 00:43:26,730
It's not a theorem.

1035
00:43:26,870 --> 00:43:27,790
It's hardly a theorem.

1036
00:43:28,150 --> 00:43:30,250
C also commutes with H.

1037
00:43:31,430 --> 00:43:32,090
How do I know?

1038
00:43:34,730 --> 00:43:36,090
Let's put an I in here.

1039
00:43:36,290 --> 00:43:37,630
Why am I putting an I in there?

1040
00:43:40,630 --> 00:43:42,450
The commutator of two Hermitian operators

1041
00:43:42,450 --> 00:43:43,510
is not Hermitian.

1042
00:43:43,550 --> 00:43:44,490
It's anti-Hermitian.

1043
00:43:46,750 --> 00:43:48,830
The commutator of X and P is I.

1044
00:43:49,570 --> 00:43:51,090
If you want a Hermitian operator,

1045
00:43:51,350 --> 00:43:52,350
you have to put an I here.

1046
00:43:52,450 --> 00:43:54,150
So let's suppose that C is

1047
00:43:54,150 --> 00:43:55,850
the commutator of A and B

1048
00:43:55,850 --> 00:43:56,970
except with an extra I.

1049
00:43:57,330 --> 00:43:59,110
Then C is a Hermitian operator.

1050
00:44:02,529 --> 00:44:04,870
And let me show you why it's conserved.

1051
00:44:04,930 --> 00:44:06,570
It's conserved for a trivial reason.

1052
00:44:08,030 --> 00:44:11,110
Let's think about the commutator of C with H.

1053
00:44:13,989 --> 00:44:16,530
That's ABH minus H.

1054
00:44:16,630 --> 00:44:16,730
That's ABH minus H.

1055
00:44:16,730 --> 00:44:21,190
AB is equal to C,

1056
00:44:21,930 --> 00:44:23,450
apart from the factor of I.

1057
00:44:24,650 --> 00:44:27,050
So the commutator of C with H

1058
00:44:27,050 --> 00:44:29,850
is proportional to ABH minus HAB.

1059
00:44:30,710 --> 00:44:32,690
But now all we have to do is say,

1060
00:44:32,750 --> 00:44:32,890
look,

1061
00:44:32,890 --> 00:44:34,630
we know that B commutes with H.

1062
00:44:34,790 --> 00:44:35,490
That's an assumption.

1063
00:44:36,090 --> 00:44:37,400
That means that we can

1064
00:44:37,400 --> 00:44:38,710
move B to the other side.

1065
00:44:39,730 --> 00:44:41,750
Once we've moved B to the other side,

1066
00:44:42,310 --> 00:44:44,530
we know that A commutes with H.

1067
00:44:44,770 --> 00:44:45,810
That's also an assumption.

1068
00:44:45,810 --> 00:44:47,650
So we can move A to the other side.

1069
00:44:51,230 --> 00:44:51,890
And that,

1070
00:44:51,890 --> 00:44:52,210
of course,

1071
00:44:52,210 --> 00:44:53,030
is equal to 0.

1072
00:44:53,850 --> 00:44:56,610
So if A and B both commute with the Hamiltonian,

1073
00:44:57,230 --> 00:45:04,010
then the commutator of A and B

1074
00:45:04,010 --> 00:45:05,930
also commute with the Hamiltonian.

1075
00:45:07,150 --> 00:45:07,750
In fact,

1076
00:45:07,750 --> 00:45:09,970
the product A and B commute with the Hamiltonian.

1077
00:45:10,330 --> 00:45:11,670
But the reason we don't

1078
00:45:11,670 --> 00:45:13,010
consider the commutator is because...

1079
00:45:13,010 --> 00:45:13,410
Sorry.

1080
00:45:14,250 --> 00:45:17,390
The product of A and B commute with the Hamiltonian.

1081
00:45:18,390 --> 00:45:20,290
Certainly the commutator does.

1082
00:45:20,990 --> 00:45:21,470
Okay?

1083
00:45:23,510 --> 00:45:25,230
I'm not so interested in the product

1084
00:45:25,230 --> 00:45:27,130
because it's not generally Hermitian.

1085
00:45:27,710 --> 00:45:29,630
It's the commutator which is Hermitian.

1086
00:45:31,070 --> 00:45:32,550
So there's an example

1087
00:45:35,709 --> 00:45:37,570
where given two symmetries,

1088
00:45:37,650 --> 00:45:39,030
if they don't commute,

1089
00:45:39,150 --> 00:45:40,530
you generate a third symmetry.

1090
00:45:40,710 --> 00:45:42,070
And it might be an independent one.

1091
00:45:42,090 --> 00:45:42,750
It might be a new thing.

1092
00:45:44,310 --> 00:45:46,730
Once you have A and B and C,

1093
00:45:46,930 --> 00:45:48,270
you can play the game again.

1094
00:45:49,250 --> 00:45:51,850
Commute C with A and B.

1095
00:45:52,950 --> 00:45:53,950
See what you get.

1096
00:45:54,150 --> 00:45:57,130
You may get something that just reproduces

1097
00:45:57,130 --> 00:45:58,550
or that's just a linear combination

1098
00:45:58,550 --> 00:46:00,590
of the three that you started with.

1099
00:46:01,990 --> 00:46:03,330
Or you may get something new.

1100
00:46:03,370 --> 00:46:03,950
You may get D.

1101
00:46:05,370 --> 00:46:07,810
You keep doing this and doing this and doing this

1102
00:46:07,810 --> 00:46:09,850
until you don't get something new.

1103
00:46:10,630 --> 00:46:11,950
You might never end.

1104
00:46:11,950 --> 00:46:14,130
You might get an infinite number

1105
00:46:14,130 --> 00:46:16,010
of different symmetries.

1106
00:46:16,510 --> 00:46:19,190
That's rare and that's unusual and it's bizarre.

1107
00:46:19,930 --> 00:46:22,030
Or it will close eventually

1108
00:46:22,030 --> 00:46:27,070
and you'll have some finite number of symmetries

1109
00:46:28,469 --> 00:46:31,270
which are all independent of each other

1110
00:46:31,950 --> 00:46:35,490
and which form a kind of closed system

1111
00:46:35,490 --> 00:46:36,970
when you commute them,

1112
00:46:37,890 --> 00:46:39,690
when you commute the generators.

1113
00:46:40,530 --> 00:46:41,270
Question?

1114
00:46:41,270 --> 00:46:41,690
Yeah.

1115
00:46:42,030 --> 00:46:43,810
Just to make sure I understand your argument,

1116
00:46:43,910 --> 00:46:45,590
what you showed was that

1117
00:46:45,590 --> 00:46:47,270
if you have A and B

1118
00:46:47,270 --> 00:46:48,130
that commute with H,

1119
00:46:48,290 --> 00:46:50,370
then the product A and B commutes with A.

1120
00:46:50,370 --> 00:46:50,730
It does.

1121
00:46:50,950 --> 00:46:53,570
And then since the commutator of A and B

1122
00:46:53,570 --> 00:46:54,950
is just A and B minus B A,

1123
00:46:55,729 --> 00:46:57,350
then you'll get the full commutation.

1124
00:46:57,670 --> 00:46:57,810
Yeah.

1125
00:46:59,930 --> 00:47:00,370
Right.

1126
00:47:00,490 --> 00:47:01,750
So eventually,

1127
00:47:01,750 --> 00:47:04,890
if you have a few symmetries,

1128
00:47:05,389 --> 00:47:07,850
you can start commuting them and commuting them

1129
00:47:07,850 --> 00:47:08,450
among themselves,

1130
00:47:09,629 --> 00:47:11,250
being guaranteed that what you get

1131
00:47:11,270 --> 00:47:12,170
is another symmetry,

1132
00:47:12,470 --> 00:47:16,850
which may be just a trivial superposition

1133
00:47:16,850 --> 00:47:19,630
of the original ones or it may be something new.

1134
00:47:19,910 --> 00:47:21,050
If it's something new,

1135
00:47:21,050 --> 00:47:22,130
good.

1136
00:47:23,090 --> 00:47:26,690
Put it into your list and commute some more.

1137
00:47:27,350 --> 00:47:27,910
Eventually,

1138
00:47:27,910 --> 00:47:29,450
you'll either run out of them

1139
00:47:30,070 --> 00:47:31,250
or you won't,

1140
00:47:31,270 --> 00:47:33,710
but I'm particularly interested in the situations

1141
